# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Cumulus — environment configuration example
#
# READ THIS FIRST — how "secrets" actually work in this project:
#
# Cumulus is a STATIC, client-only PWA (no server, no build step). Anything
# the browser executes is, by definition, shipped to the browser. You cannot
# "hide" a key in client code — a .env only helps once you add a build step
# or a server-side proxy that injects/keeps values.
#
# The values below are the PUBLISHABLE client keys and are SAFE to expose:
#   • SUPABASE_ANON_KEY — the public "anon" key. Access is enforced by
#     Supabase Row Level Security (RLS), NOT by keeping this key secret.
#     Harden your RLS policies; that is the real security boundary.
#   • MAPBOX_TOKEN — a public token. Restrict it to your domain(s) via URL
#     restrictions in the Mapbox account dashboard.
#   • STRIPE_PUBLISHABLE_KEY — Stripe's pk_test_/pk_live_ key. Safe to expose;
#     it can only start a checkout/verification flow, never move money or
#     read data on its own.
#
# NEVER commit or ship a Supabase `service_role` key, a Stripe secret key
# (sk_...), or a Stripe webhook signing secret (whsec_...) in client code —
# those belong only in Edge Function secrets (`supabase secrets set`),
# never in this file or in src/js/config.js.
#
# ── How to use ──
# For local/other environments, either edit src/js/config.js directly, or
# create a gitignored src/js/config.local.js that sets window.CUMULUS_CONFIG
# BEFORE config.js runs, e.g.:
#   window.CUMULUS_CONFIG = {
#     SUPABASE_URL: '...', SUPABASE_ANON_KEY: '...', MAPBOX_TOKEN: '...'
#   };
# If you later add a bundler (Vite, etc.), map these VITE_* vars into
# window.CUMULUS_CONFIG at build time.
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

SUPABASE_URL=https://your-project.supabase.co
SUPABASE_ANON_KEY=your-public-anon-key
MAPBOX_TOKEN=pk.your-public-mapbox-token
STRIPE_PUBLISHABLE_KEY=pk_test_your-public-stripe-key
